<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="372" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,767,786,1321]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,786,809]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">Description.</emphasis>
Body size large, 
<quantity box="[466,545,786,809]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="9" pageNumber="372" unit="mm" value="3.8">3.8 mm</quantity>
in length (excluding rostrum and deeply inserted head). Rostrum with pterygia very widely exposed in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[579,670,850,873]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[151,182,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1209]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,186,1214]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Yagder serratus gen. &amp; sp. nov., details. A–C – rostral apex, dorsal (A), left lateral (B), ventral (C); D – head, left lateral; E–F – left antenna, lateral (E), distal part magnified (F); G–I – tarsi, left front leg (G–H), left middle leg (I); J – elytral apex; K–L – dissected female abdominal apex, ventral (K) and right latero-ventral (L)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5820904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5820904/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
), apical two antennomeres of funicle longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[662,751,882,905]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[151,182,1784,1803]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1771]" captionTargetId="figure-13@2.[151,1436,188,1773]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Yagder serratus gen. &amp; sp. nov., habitus, dorsal (A), ventral (B) and left fronto-lateral (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5820901" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5820901/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). Pronotal and elytral contour in dorsal view with large saw-like serrations especially evident towards elytral apex (
<figureCitation box="[159,236,978,1001]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[151,182,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,189,1209]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[151,1436,186,1214]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Yagder serratus gen. &amp; sp. nov., details. A–C – rostral apex, dorsal (A), left lateral (B), ventral (C); D – head, left lateral; E–F – left antenna, lateral (E), distal part magnified (F); G–I – tarsi, left front leg (G–H), left middle leg (I); J – elytral apex; K–L – dissected female abdominal apex, ventral (K) and right latero-ventral (L)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5820904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5820904/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">Fig. 2J</figureCitation>
). Abdomen with ventrites I and II densely deeply punctate. DNA: 
<accessionNumber box="[332,461,1010,1033]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MW201355" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">MW201355</accessionNumber>
(COI), 
<accessionNumber box="[550,679,1010,1033]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MW201457" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">MW201457</accessionNumber>
(ITS2) and 
<accessionNumber box="[196,326,1042,1065]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MW201468" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">MW201468</accessionNumber>
(28S).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="372" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,767,786,1321]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,243,1074,1097]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">Biology.</emphasis>
A single female was sifted from leaf litter in primary mountain forest. Multiple samples taken at the same time and location by J. T. Longino and M. G. Branstetter failed to produce additional specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="372" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,767,786,1321]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,1202,1225]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is the Latin adjective meaning “serrated, toothed like a saw”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="372" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,767,786,1321]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,298,1266,1289]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[714,760,1266,1289]" pageId="9" pageNumber="372">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
